{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"alias":"cold-stall-chalk","description":"## Context\nrebar's write path commits one git object graph per event (~3.3 commits/event on the tickets branch). This is the git-issue-style high-bloat pattern: the durable way to bound growth is to create fewer objects at the source, the git-bug `operationPack` pattern (multiple ops serialized into one blob -> one commit per Commit()). Supersedes orphan e3d0 (sleek-bur-train) and folds duplicate 39c5 (grungy-grain-drawl). Discovered from the closed bounded-git-growth epic 97e7, which addressed *reclaim* (stock gc) but explicitly left the *growth rate* at write time out of scope.\n\nPrior art (verified): git-bug operationPack (entity/dag/operation_pack.go) and entity commit/merge (entity/dag/entity.go). Experiment (this session) confirmed that append-only, uuid-per-event files converge structurally under union merge with zero conflict and zero data loss — so a batch commit preserves rebar's invariants as long as each event stays its own file.\n\nPriority note: now that stock gc reclaims (gc-config normalized), the *visible* bloat problem is handled; this epic's remaining value is mainly bulk-import/migration latency and slowing long-term commit-count growth — real but no longer urgent.\n\n## Success Criteria\n- A batch-commit write primitive exists and is adopted on the highest-churn write paths, demonstrably reducing object/commit count on a synthetic many-event run, with no regression to replay, dedup, union-merge convergence, or SNAPSHOT compaction.\n\n## Workstreams\n- WS-B1: `_store.batch_stage_and_commit(events)` — under ONE write lock: write/rename M event files (each its own unique uuid+HLC name), one `git add`, ONE commit. The single-event write path is unchanged. Preserves invariants I2 (composed events), I5 (single locked writer), and union-merge/compaction (which key off event UUIDs, not commit boundaries).\n- WS-B2: route the importer through it in chunks (first adopter; the 39c5 bulk-import case). Atomicity: a single commit of M staged files is atomic at the git level; partial staging before commit is recoverable because import is idempotent (resume by `source_id`).\n- WS-B3: optionally route the reconciler batch-apply through it (second adopter).\n- WS-B4: crash-resume/idempotent-by-`source_id` tests + union-merge + compaction regression tests + a before/after object-count benchmark on a large synthetic store.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n- [ ] `_store.batch_stage_and_commit(events)`: one lock, M event files each its own uuid-named file, one commit; single-event write path unchanged\n- [ ] Importer routes events through it in chunks; reconciler-apply optionally adopts it\n- [ ] Object-count/commit-count reduction demonstrated on a synthetic many-event run (before/after benchmark)\n- [ ] No regression: replay, dedup, cross-clone union-merge convergence, and SNAPSHOT compaction tests green\n- [ ] Crash-resume (idempotent by source_id) test proves partial-stage recovery","id":"ce4c-f963-363b-44b6","parent_id":"","priority":2,"tags":[],"ticket_type":"epic","title":"Write-time op batching (operationPack): batched-commit primitive + bulk-path adoption"},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"CREATE","timestamp":1782865661528214001,"uuid":"2c0f0fdf-26a0-46de-aca7-1d4dbff74618"}